commit_message:
Docs: Update PLUMgrid neutron services dict override

Following the change introduced by: I38e1fad4dfae24b32f4370b3da16561c42cd670d

The neutron services dictionary need not be redeclared
entirely for overidding the service enables. The plumgrid install
doc has been updated accrordingly.

Change-Id: I6d700ad5253642ca1b2a73d2eff1db6c74472b78
Signed-off-by: Javeria Khan <javeriak@plumgrid.com>
(cherry picked from commit 644c57b9c22c1bdee6dd9ad0afb9385439da3f7f)

commit_message:
Docs: Ops section - cleanup

As per discussion in the OSA docs summit session, clean up
of installation guide. This fixes typos, minor RST mark up
changes, and passive voice.

Change-Id: Ibacaabddafee465a05bcb6eec01dd3ef04b33826

commit_message:
Disable security role during major upgrades

This commit disables the security hardening role during major
upgrades by creating a temporary file. It removes the file after
a sucessful upgrade.

Change-Id: Ib32e0e317a84a443fb7fc9d3a364a16bd469b6e3
Closes-Bug: #1568029

commit_message:
Add script to validate fedora atomic images

Initially do a qemu-img check to ensure that the image is valid,
and also check that the image size is the one we expect.

Change-Id: I447372df99303f40fd033b9673ec6cc370e65477

commit_message:
Adding a few #nosec tags to prepare for Bandit usage

This commit adds a few #nosec tags for non-issues.  I've examined
the code and determined that these don't represent security issues
so we should add a #nosec tag that tells Bandit not to find these
issues in the future.

Closes-Bug: #1577498
Change-Id: Ic37216c08442c700c64118c78cfb46e6cedd237c

commit_message:
Improved logging for memcached (OSA calling part)

- Moved to the right folder to get it accessed on bare metal
  when containerized
- Prepared the logging when on metal
- Rsyslog and logrotation implemented

Closes-Bug: #1569171

Depends-On: I3a1c2f50ab63b55b39318ba40c0921f6b738cafb
Change-Id: I61b526334929349f9b10bda5d62b76459ebcf534

and maximum memory bw on a given NUMA node.

Co-Authored-By: Jay Pipes <jaypipes@gmail.com>

commit_message:
Allow NUMA based reporting for Monitors

This patchset allows monitors to report NUMA based metrics
It is a follow up to the work on creating a MonitorMetric Object.

Additionally, it defines two new fields to return the current
and maximum memory bw on a given NUMA node.

Co-Authored-By: Jay Pipes <jaypipes@gmail.com>

Change-Id: I6a0d589901851e392c75ab7ae754c454026e939f
Partially-Implements: blueprint memory-bw

commit_message:
Make .git an optional suffix for GIT_REPOs

Some people are nutty (namely myself) and mount filesystems that have
copies of all the OpenStack repos cloned, and they do not have ".git" in
the repo name.

Blame it on jogo's great "mustached-bear" tool

https://github.com/jogo/mustached-bear

Change-Id: Ib7e417760d234648cf6b14f4a5f6b0e63a4e6943

Philippe: eliminating unnecessary inconsistencies is usually a good move - fewer things to keep in your head, and it makes scripting easier. Is the information being eliminated available elsewhere?'}, {'account_id': 14525, 'date': '2016-04-28 15:38:51.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

Philippe, Miles thanks for review.

It makes troubleshooting easier because at the moment ironic node and VM are associated via mac address. To find VM console on which deployment is going you need to do ironic node-port-list, for i in $(virsh list --all); do virsh domiflist $i |grep <mac-address>; done
In case Ironic node name is the same as for VM you just need to do ironic node-list and you know what VM is associated with it.

Secondly: at the moment there is only one way to find VM for Ironic node. Which is needed for cleaning tests, see latest request in this chain. There will be a lot of ugly shell/python code to find VM for node. That is why this change is needed.

We do not using VM name elsewhere. Net bridge name may be found in local.conf or via brctl show. Not sure that it is a big lose.'}, {'account_id': 18893, 'date': '2016-04-28 15:54:11.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

That definitely sounds like a win - and it's the kind of thing I meant by "makes scripting easier" :-)'}, {'account_id': 7933, 'date': '2016-04-28 18:42:05.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

So if I understand this clearly, virsh list --all will return node-1, node-2, node-x and so does ironic node-list right?'}, {'account_id': 14525, 'date': '2016-04-29 06:32:34.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

Yes, virsh list --all will return node-0, node-1 ... node-x'}, {'account_id': 7933, 'date': '2016-04-29 13:27:10.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Code-Review+1'}, {'account_id': 2889, 'date': '2016-05-01 15:18:51.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Code-Review+2'}, {'account_id': 6610, 'date': '2016-05-03 08:15:47.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Code-Review+1'}, {'account_id': 6773, 'date': '2016-05-03 08:34:03.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Code-Review+2 Workflow+1

[{'created': '2016-05-03 07:58:12.000000000', 'message': 'Add dependencies for paramiko 2.0

Paramiko version 2.0 has been released. It now uses the Python library
cryptography. Installing this requires additional system packages. This
commit adds in the appropriate packages required by cryptography based
on its documentation [1].

An alternative approach would have been to constrain the version of
Paramiko however the project describes the 1.x versions as relying on
insecure dependencies [2].

[1] https://cryptography.io/en/latest/installation/
[2] http://www.paramiko.org/installing.html

Change-Id: Ia1b5678bb9bb5e5902e6ec8a7a1ba2ee65a90337
'}]
commit_message:
Add dependencies for paramiko 2.0

Paramiko version 2.0 has been released. It now uses the Python library
cryptography. Installing this requires additional system packages. This
commit adds in the appropriate packages required by cryptography based
on its documentation [1].

An alternative approach would have been to constrain the version of
Paramiko however the project describes the 1.x versions as relying on
insecure dependencies [2].

[1] https://cryptography.io/en/latest/installation/
[2] http://www.paramiko.org/installing.html

Change-Id: Ia1b5678bb9bb5e5902e6ec8a7a1ba2ee65a90337

commit_message:
Add dependencies for paramiko 2.0

Paramiko version 2.0 has been released. It now uses the Python library
cryptography. Installing this requires additional system packages. This
commit adds in the appropriate packages required by cryptography based
on its documentation [1].

An alternative approach would have been to constrain the version of
Paramiko however the project describes the 1.x versions as relying on
insecure dependencies [2].

[1] https://cryptography.io/en/latest/installation/
[2] http://www.paramiko.org/installing.html

Change-Id: Ic05d3273ba2f6be85d502ef075478c9f98892eef

commit_message:
Add dependencies for paramiko 2.0

Paramiko version 2.0 has been released. It now uses the Python library
cryptography. Installing this requires additional system packages. This
commit adds in the appropriate packages required by cryptography based
on its documentation [1].

An alternative approach would have been to constrain the version of
Paramiko however the project describes the 1.x versions as relying on
insecure dependencies [2].

[1] https://cryptography.io/en/latest/installation/
[2] http://www.paramiko.org/installing.html

Change-Id: Ibea8a8cb8312ac94590acf14058bbd8012c77057

This adds a variable IRONIC_EXTRA_PXE_PARAMS that can be used in
devstack configuration to add additional pxe parameters to the
pxe_append_params config in ironic.conf.

Change-Id: I08d468defd3187f7837801c99ee625928cc92c47
"}]
commit_message:
Devstack: allow extra PXE params

This adds a variable IRONIC_EXTRA_PXE_PARAMS that can be used in
devstack configuration to add additional pxe parameters to the
pxe_append_params config in ironic.conf.

For instance, someone could use this to set 'noapic' in the kernel
command line for pxe boots.

Change-Id: I08d468defd3187f7837801c99ee625928cc92c47

commit_message:
Docs: Update PLUMgrid neutron services dict override

Following the change introduced by: I38e1fad4dfae24b32f4370b3da16561c42cd670d

The neutron services dictionary need not be redeclared
entirely for overidding the service enables. The plumgrid install
doc has been updated accrordingly.

Change-Id: I6d700ad5253642ca1b2a73d2eff1db6c74472b78
Signed-off-by: Javeria Khan <javeriak@plumgrid.com>
(cherry picked from commit 644c57b9c22c1bdee6dd9ad0afb9385439da3f7f)

commit_message:
Add stacklock for resource_signal

when the stack is in other actions, the stack should be
locked, and the resources of the stack can't be signaled.

Change-Id: Ic09255c0fbea127ac36647e9277056eb41e74de4
Closes-bug: #1310648

commit_message:
[do not merge] Dirty hacks set for 0.0.4

* Input task is changed now on top you are specifing list,
each object of this list has the same structure as task before

* You can sepcifgy tags for test case

* 2 more context to disable Admin and Regular cleanups:
  no_cleanup and no_admin_cleanup

* Create tenants with random suffix in users context.
  Workaround for MOS keystone bug

Change-Id: I1f473423934de32222469a456138b22dcd8ea020

commit_message:
Stop using trusty-backports haproxy with >= L

For < L we use backport haproxy when prefer-ipv6=True but
should not use it with >= L.

Change-Id: I61d641e62945ce86d1ebe33724e1c207c2b0cfe0
Closes-Bug: 1577243

Notes on the utils.terminal_width implementation:

    added later by engineers who have access to these environments)

The previous column width behaviour is retained in the following
scenarios:
  - utils.terminal_width returns None for any of the reasons stated
    above
  - --max-width is specified

Closes-Bug: #1485847

commit_message:
Resize columns to fit screen width

Many outputs from python-openstackclient will exceed the width of the
user's terminal. When this happens even by one character, the whole
PrettyTable layout becomes very difficult to read.

This change adds a utils.terminal_width method and uses that to
calculate optimal max_width values to fit the table into the
available width.

Notes on the utils.terminal_width implementation:
- Determining width by consuming the COLUMNS environment variable is
  avoided so that existing scripts which pipe output for value parsing
  continue to behave deterministically.
- python3 has support for getting the terminal size, so this is used
  when available
- The python2 fallback uses the same linux tty detection found in many
  python recipes
- None is returned when width cannot be determined, such as
  - Not a tty, because the command is being piped to other commands, or
    it is being run in a non-interactive environment
  - A python2 environment running on Windows or OSX (these can always be
    added later by engineers who have access to these environments)

The previous column width behaviour is retained in the following
scenarios:
  - utils.terminal_width returns None for any of the reasons stated
    above
  - --max-width is specified

Closes-Bug: #1485847

Change-Id: I51b6157929f0b4a9ce66990e3e64ce9e730862c2

commit_message:
[Devstack] Set proper driver mode for ZFSonLinux driver

Set opt "driver_handles_share_servers" to "False" value if
ZFSonLinux share driver is enabled.

Change-Id: Ia4b8abedd18e5002a3068beb3732d26ec21b35df
Closes-Bug: #1560126

commit_message:
Support interface drivers that don't support mtu parameter for plug_new

The method signature before Mitaka did not have the mtu= parameter. We
should continue supporting the old signature, since it can be used in
out of tree interface drivers. The class is part of public neutron API,
so we should make an effort to not break out of tree code.

Local modifications:
- don't issue a deprecation warning in minor release update.

Change-Id: I8e0c07c76fd0b4c55b66c20ebe29cdb7c07d6f27
Closes-Bug: #1570392
(cherry picked from commit 8a86ba1d014a5e758c0569aaf16cfe92492cc7f1)

commit_message:
Only prevent l3 port deletion if router exists

This patch modifies the prevent_l3_port_deletion method to
actually look up the router_id in the device_owner field to
confirm that the router exists before claiming the port is
in use. This will allow users to delete ports that may have
been orphaned due to race conditions in the cleanup of router
interfaces.

Conflicts:
	neutron/tests/unit/db/test_l3_db.py

Closes-Bug: #1566678
Partial-Bug: #1540271
Change-Id: Ieffe632f3f3098baf202d3795ab5182982e234bd
(cherry picked from commit 3b41808b8624f5442d65ba638d1a2c1bdc22be00)

commit_message:
Consume FWaaS plugin queue in RPC workers

This patch adds all RPC workers to consumers of FWaaS plugin queue.
This is important for DVR-enabled deployments with hundreds
of agents.

Change-Id: I656ef6248379c845c4c7862fabd26eedd8b7fd46
Depends-On: I6fea7f409c91b25d2c35b038d6100fdfa85d1905
Related-Bug: #1498844
(cherry picked from commit bda2c484cb25d3a02d9beceab83873bd60569e46)

commit_message:
Consume service plugins queues in RPC workers.

This patch adds all RPC workers to consumers of service
plugins queues such as metering and l3-plugin.
This is important for DVR-enabled deployments with hundreds
of agents.

Closes-Bug: #1498844
(cherry picked from commit 5be613490deebf494f2ecbbcd8cb5dd0d6f5e1b3)

===

Also include the following fix that keeps backwards compatibility with
plugins that don't implement start_rpc_listeners method:

Check if plugin supports starting rpc listeners

When neutron starts an rpc worker, it checks if the plugin has the method
"start_rpc_listeners".  Since most plugins inherit from a base class, and
that base class implements the start_rpc_listeners method and raises
NotImplementedError, the rpc worker will attempt to call that method.
It should just catch the NotImplementedError and continue on.

Change-Id: Ie1830b6140acffffd0f283a0d8eefa52067f7650
Closes-Bug: 1551542
(cherry picked from commit cd7be292a8d1fb4ce913c4e7fbfc55fda033ffbe)

===

Change-Id: I6fea7f409c91b25d2c35b038d6100fdfa85d1905

commit_message:
Make Plan parameterss a DictOfDict

Plan parameters were a JSON string. In order to get and set
parameters using a key, they are now represented as a dictionary of
dictionaries.

Change-Id: I431d0dac80819ca25c8488fe25a00156e8863bdc

commit_message:
[WIP] Fuel support for CentOS 7

Update mirror creation (certain parts are no longer needed, like kernel-lt or
efidisk.img).

Reflect migration to GRUB2 in CentOS 7.

Cherry-pick https://review.openstack.org/#/c/232496
(which removes CentOS image building)

Remove everything that is missing in repos or was renamed. Below
is the full list of changes ("->" means package was renamed):
- bash (part of the core group)
- htop;
- ceph;
- docker-io -> docker;
- daemonize (should be replaced by systemd anyway);
- device-mapper-persistent-data;
- fence-agents -> fence-agents-all;
- fuel-createmirror
- fuel-library
- fuelmenu
- fuel-ostf
- kernel-lt
- kmod-hpsa
- libfcgi
- lxc
- megaraid_sas
- nailgun-agent
- nailgun-mcagents
- nginx
- nmap-ncat
- python-amqplib
- python-argparse
- python-beautifulsoup4
- python-cherrypy
- python-daemon
- python-daemonize
- python-fabric
- python-fuelclient
- python-fysom
- python-glanceclient
- python-html5lib
- python-importlib
- python-lockfile
- python-MarkupSafe
- python-meld3
- python-nose-cover3
- python-oslo-config
- python-ordereddict
- python-pip
- python-PrettyTable
- python-pypcap
- python-tablib
- python-waitress
- python-webpy
- python-wsgilog
- python-wsgiproxy2
- python-wsgiref
- rpm (part of the core)
- ruby21*
- rubygem-deep_merge
- rubygem-netaddr
- rubygem-openstack
- ruby-irb
- ruby-rdoc -> rubygem-rdoc
- ruby-ri
- send2syslog
- shotgun
- subscription-manager
- supervisor
- uwsgi
- uwsgi-plugin-python
- vim

commit_message:
Added check offline nodes before start provisioning

Also added flag 'force' that disables this check
Also moved formatting message for offline nodes in separate function,
introduced limit for number of nodes in message.

Change-Id: I20196fcd478de11c4053931ea674e6c25aecfd48
Closes-Bug: 1547045

commit_message:
System test examples on py.test

A case is a class, steps in the methods
    test_in_class.py

A case is a method, class is a test suite
    test_in_method.py

Each file contains 3 examples
    - Get from manager already bootstrapped slaves and deploy cluster
      in test (bvt_2)
    - Get from manager already deployed cluster push config from test
      (bvt2_2)
    - Get from manager already deployed cluster get config from template
      (bvt2_3)

Howto run tests:
    export POOL_DEFAULT="10.109.0.0/16:24"
    export ISO_PATH=/path/to/FUEL9.0.iso
    export ENV_NAME="pytest_test"
    PYTHONPATH=".:$PYTHONPATH" \
        pytest -p no:django -vvv -s systest/tests/test_in_method.py -m bvt_2_2

    Select file test_in_method.py or test_in_class.py
    Select test bvt_2, bvt_2_2, bvt_2_3

Change-Id: Ia86191bae109fd411422023ba5edf3c465fc677d

commit_message:
Use glance-swift conf for swift backend

For working with Swift backend, Glance needs authentication parameters,
which are supplied to Swift when making calls to its storage system.
Glance will use information from the file specified under parameter
swift_store_config_file. When this parameter is set to the same file
(glance-api.conf), we have lot of non-critical errors in glance-api
log, because of 'Invalid format of swift store config'.

The same problem, when we have RadosGW.

Change-Id: I18ee8f68f7ce793d2580685e79ed636556c57ddd
Related-bug: #1540890

Thank you for your first contribution to OpenStack.

    Your patch will now be tested automatically by OpenStack testing frameworks
    and once the automatic tests pass, it will be reviewed by other friendly
    developers. They will give you feedback and may require you to refine it.

    People seldom get their patch approved on the first try, so don't be
    concerned if requested to make corrections. Feel free to modify your patch
    and resubmit a new change-set.

    Patches usually take 3 to 7 days to be reviewed so be patient and be
    available on IRC to ask and answer questions about your work. Also it
    takes generally at least a couple of weeks for cores to get around to
    reviewing code. The more you participate in the community the more
    rewarding it is for you. You may also notice that the more you get to know
    people and get to be known, the faster your patches will be reviewed and
    eventually approved. Get to know others and become known by doing code
    reviews: anybody can do it, and it's a great way to learn the code base.

    Thanks again for supporting OpenStack, we look forward to working with you.

Please take into account that we also have Load Deployed Settings button on the Settings tab.

commit_message:
tripleo.sh: deploy missing deps to run rdopkg

rdopkg requires paramiko which requires cryptography which requires
libffi-devel openssl-devel, that are not installed by default.

This patch is a workaround until
https://review.openstack.org/#/c/311734/ is merged and a new image is
built.

Change-Id: I22bc5d045c05837e736a1f1038146d1b363d518f

commit_message:
Make puppet-gerrit beaker rspec non voting

Turns out that our puppet cannot currently install gerrit because
gerrit's init system relies on downloading packages from locations that
404. This means that the beaker rspec tests will fail. Handle this in
the short term by making the job non voting until bouncy castle can be
convinced to keep hosting the files or gerrit can be updated to get
different files.

Change-Id: Ifbae7dd1c768527e0d4e39b6bcbbc31da923d733

commit_message:
SMBFS: Fix initialize connection issues caused by in-use images

In some cases, if the volume is in use, attempting to retrieve
image informations will raise permission errors.

This is mainly affecting live migration when having volumes attached
over SMB, when using Hyper-V.

The only information that we attempt to retrieve in this case is
the volume format. We can easily avoid these kind of issues by always
using the volume format as an extension for the image files (at
the moment we do this only for vhd/x images).

Change-Id: Id1c713b2d3047c5ee5746207d73059b19ce4563b
Closes-Bug: #1554027

commit_message:
Use paginate_query from oslo_db

The paginate_query method was copied from nova which was copied
from glance. Now it is available in oslo_db.

Check and convert the sort keys and sort directions for
consumption by the oslo_db version of the method, and fix up
some grammar in the exception messages.

This work is related to the neutron-lib effort. The lib should
not propagate neutron's copy of paginate_query().

Related-Blueprint: neutron-lib

Change-Id: Ie7da16b94fa2023c9c3d84d96d55f33d0f76903f

commit_message:
test_subnetpools_extensions: Correct the extension name

Neutron doesn't have an extension named "subnetpools".
It should be "subnet_allocation".

Also, rename the file to match with the name of the extension.

Closes-Bug: #1517920
Change-Id: I6d52906a650dfd51b94cd8d49bcce23add19d1bf

commit_message:
Fix oslo_service stop/start mechanism

Also we miss to call inherited stop method somtimes. That was
not stopping oslo.service resources. This change fixes that.

This allows us to stop the refresh_pipeline periodic thread on stop,
now.

Change-Id: Ib8498aa95bbca2b1d42d3579891f5f0c5ec67268

commit_message:
Updated instructions for API migration files

Provides pointer to the api-site patch, plus adds a section for
the overall build and publish process. Should work for both
migrated services as well as new services.

Change-Id: I1ff691d9439096a7f38e94f5c01e61a105f48b80

commit_message:
Add support to set env to a container

Docker run support an option to set environment variables
to a container. container-create in Magnum also needs this.
This will help for the user to create a container with some
environment variables. Support two options:
--env key=value
--env-file /xxx/env_file

Implements: blueprint support-to-set-env-variables

Change-Id: I6fdfaafbeb431825961485b111397753e7866379

commit_message:
Fix format_labels with same keys

When format_labels with same keys, the type of value
will be a list. It's not correct. This patch fix this.
When have same keys, should not append the new value,
just overwrite the old value.

Change-Id: I6f742a1eef006bbad7581f5cc3365ca680bf5499
Closes-Bug: #1521461

commit_message:
Cleanup tox environment

Since we do not build DocBook XML anymore, we have removed the jobs for
this and thus can remove the support for these also from tox.ini.

checksyntax, checklinks and checkdeletions are DocBook XML only targets,
so remove them.

Change-Id: Iaa663c03fd6e2976208e20ba03dbab4d8d82b2ce
Depends-On: I9f5944eb9db06fe2ff9088f22048c198b2921237

commit_message:
Convert glossary to RST

We do not need the DocBook XML glossary anymore, since we do not build
any DocBook guides that use it.

Add instead the RST version of the document to git.
Adjust scripts to not build or publish the glossary anymore.

Change-Id: Id4bfef7666690e6d08291f664751db7a4d4d5983

commit_message:
remove assert in favor an if/else

the assert usage in the NonNegativeAction has the potential to allow
unexpected behavior when the python is byte-compiled with optimization
turned on.

Changes
* remove assert in favor of if/else in NonNegativeAction class
* add type specifier to parser arguments for non-negative actions
* correct tests for new int based values

Change-Id: I093e7440b8beff4f179e2c4ed81daff82704c40e
Closes-Bug: #1576375

commit_message:
Create identity-credentials relation

Charms use this relation to obtain keystone credentials without
creating a service catalog entry. Set 'username' only on the relation
and keystone will set defaults and return authentication details.

Possible relation settings:
username: Username to be created.
project: Project (tenant) name to be created. Defaults to services
         project.
requested_roles: Comma delimited list of roles to be created
requested_grants: Comma delimited list of roles to be granted.
                  Defaults to Admin role.
domain: Keystone v3 domain the user will be created in.
        Defaults to the Default domain.

Change-Id: I465d2273560d86752d1bfc7497a9139a9604f814

q-vpn log is not expected for non vpnaas jobs. Even more so, vpnaas
tempest gate does not even run q-vpn service, instead relying on

So just replace q-vpn log (which never exists) with l3 agent log, which

commit_message:
Fixed link to l3 agent in tempest-logs

q-vpn log is not expected for non vpnaas jobs. Even more so, vpnaas
tempest gate does not even run q-vpn service, instead relying on
neutron-vpnaas service defined in devstack plugin.

So just replace q-vpn log (which never exists) with l3 agent log, which
is a reasonable default for neutron gate logdirs.

Change-Id: Ie91b3a724c22f9262aa1925be5505fe118d93751

commit_message:
Fix deprecation warning in tackerclient

Changed _extract_service_catalog to match neutronclient to remove
deprecation warnings when attr is provided without filter_value to
get_urls().

Change-Id: Ic58060bdf50ce1f3834324372f1a375fbd15beb6
Closes-Bug: #1570641

commit_message:
Remove doubled configuration in local.conf

When DEVSTACK_GATE_VIRT_DRIVER has been set to ironic, in function
setup_localrc, VIRT_DRIVER=ironic will be set to local.conf twice.
This fix remove the second write.

Change-Id: I6c0e7649366e3567b9342e4f83489dbae0229c2b
Closes-Bug: 1561279

commit_message:
Consider to log a package list for pip3

When we run devstack with USE_PYTHON3=True, a package may be
installed by pip2 or pip3 depending on package classifier.
So we should try to log a package list by pip2 and pip3.

Change-Id: I06e2559e852f0dabbbbb8f6c0dc081cedb745b60

commit_message:
Just pass None for plugin if auth_type is None

keystoneuath Session does null-auth when auth plugin is None.

Change-Id: I1ae66402f94c12d1f87061ec124491c47875483a

commit_message:
Add ability to pass in prompt callback

Some things, like legacy CLIs and OSC may want to prompt the user for a
password. That's great, let them do it. Also, provide both a base class
for callbacks to implement, and a very simple command line prompting
class that only returns passwords.

Change-Id: Iff27ebcf410afc394ef9bad7dafaed703287cc8f

commit_message:
devstack-vm-gate-wrap: pin paramiko==1.16.0

paramiki > 1.16.0 requires python-cryptography, but TripleO CI does not
handle libffi-devel and openssl-devel packages, it's a WIP in DIB.

Until we fix it in DIB, this patch is a workaround so we can unblock CIs
that use this script, TripleO CI included.

Change-Id: I05755e5374472fb95a4ff9d0dc03dbd33bba627f

commit_message:
Instance Detail Console Error is not consistent

project/instances: Detail view -> Console ...
ON error, it gives a button that just reloads the page.  This
experience is odd and is not consistent with other alert messages.

Just removed that button ... its not necessary.

Closes-bug: #1570591

Change-Id: Ica7fa97cf249fa76809e8e8ac6750cec37d6eee6

commit_message:
Add retry to rename func

This change adds a retry to the overall rename operation.  The CI
testing has found a few etag issues from the REST API when this is
invoked and this change will provide some additional retries to ensure
that the overall rename goes through.

Change-Id: Ib68bfb72fd0b755fe065c36153c4dceffc117ebc
Closes-Bug: 1570927
(cherry picked from commit dd776b9a7d56679e290262f248beaf01e89ac815)

commit_message:
Nova disk quota tracking

Nova currently does not have a quota categorization for tracking storage
consumption, which encourages users to disproportionately consume
storage resources through Nova (image-booted instances, LVM-backed
instances, etc.) instead of using Cinder volumes, where quota is
tracked. This blueprint proposes the addition of a new quota category to
track these non-Cinder usages of disk space.

Change-Id: Icd90f684f98eccbafec976d730eb694f0b0ed404

commit_message:
Add retry to rename func

This change adds a retry to the overall rename operation.  The CI
testing has found a few etag issues from the REST API when this is
invoked and this change will provide some additional retries to ensure
that the overall rename goes through.

Change-Id: Ib68bfb72fd0b755fe065c36153c4dceffc117ebc
Closes-Bug: 1570927

commit_message:
Fix possible race condition in build script

This fixes a potential race condition during the build process, where
the 'browserify' task could attempt to run before the views had been
compiled, resulting in build failure. This change makes the
'browserify' task wait for views to finish before running.

Change-Id: I8358812a90caf006c18220b643347848f15779fe

commit_message:
api version changes always requires a bump

According to the api wg [1], any api change requires a microversion bump.
Change the devref to reflect this.

[1] http://specs.openstack.org/openstack/api-wg/guidelines/
microversion_specification.html

Change-Id: Icd6502560f6709da568bd4dd09ba5a15f0b06a76
Closes-Bug: #1575902

commit_message:
Added software deployment timeout policy

A deployment can be set to skip in the event of a timeout, allowing
optional deployments (for instance, an unregister during a deployment
delete action) to not cause the stack to fail while still having a
configurable timeout. Defaults to fail if the policy is not set.

Partial-Bug: #1557764
Change-Id: I9b9b09b940793c22371165a8cd74daf937efd1f8

commit_message:
RGW >= Jewel requires pool names prefixed with zone

When deploying Jewel RGW (10.*) or above, pool names are
expected to be prefixed by the RGW client zone name.

Closes-Bug: 1573549

commit_message:
Prevent binding IPv6 addresses to Neutron interfaces

Explicitly disable IPv6 on Neutron created interfaces in the default
namespace before setting link up. Since the default behavior of IPv6 is
to bind to all interfaces as opposed to IPv4 where an address must be
explicitly configured we disable IPv6 on each interface before enabling
the interface. This avoids leaving a time window between when the
interface is enabled and when it is attached to bridge device during
which the host could be access from a tenant network.

Move disable_ipv6() from BridgeDevice to base IPDevice class so it is
usable by all interfaces. Then we explicitly disable IPv6 on veth
interfaces in the default namespaces and VXLAN and VLAN interfaces
created by the LinuxBridge agent.

In addition vlan interface is moved from LinuxBridgeManager to IPWrapper
so it can return an IPDevice object.

Closes-Bug: #1534652
Change-Id: Id879075f2d5ee42f8ff153e813e7519a4424447b
(cherry picked from commit fc8ebae0351f5b6596951cdfc5cb4259501d84f2)

commit_message:
Add non-voting puppet-4 apply jobs for infra

In anticipation of puppet 4, start running a set of non-voting jobs to
test that puppet apply works with our modules when running puppet 4.

Change-Id: Ia721f3fdd8ce14e230a1ae8c25c87040e06556ea
Depends-On: I3c7d23d47cc8c823478dc8e2652c7b8f1d06535d

commit_message:
[Trivial] Remove unnecessary executable flag for files

There are some files in trove which actually don't have main entry,
they are modules rather than scripts, hence should not have the
executable flag.

Change-Id: I08b549fd339525e29d9c3247fab87901b8bbff69

Avoid complex metaclass to define pkg.Package. It doesn't seem to
work on Python 3, and simpler code works too :-)

commit_message:
Simplify guestagent.pkg: don't use metaclass

Avoid complex metaclass to define pkg.Package. It doesn't seem to
work on Python 3, and simpler code works too :-)

Partially implements: blueprint trove-python3
Change-Id: I880527f043fcddb11926d38b5641b3a61512e27f

Safe oslo releases for the week of april 18th, 2016

libraries currently should cause any issues (which I for

commit_message:
Fix uuidgen not installed in some ubuntu installs

On some basic ubuntu install the uuidgen commands is not there causing
gnocchi installation to fail.
Add a new pre-install commands to install the package on ubuntu systems.

Change-Id: I456b2421905c383c5df39deb7f1a1819ad1c990e

commit_message:
grafana: added a dashboard with periodic jobs for neutron

Among others, we include python jobs that validate neutron unit tests
against oslo libraries from master instead of pypi. This will hopefully
raise visibility for the new failures that would affect neutron unit
tests when next oslo library releases will land PyPI and
upper-constraints.txt.

Change-Id: I0b1f67657cd8f29e34dee85b12e88af90067e62b

commit_message:
Fall back to glance API v1

In murano client we've used glance client v2, so image update worked
incorrect. Now it's necessary to fall back to glance api v1, since v2
doesn't support some needed abilities.

Change-Id: I1b0d6c9dd4075cd44133ef5111192fa602406cf2
Closes-Bug: #1572492
(cherry picked from commit 3341f488621774a621b4d37aac56d3e83b3314b2)

commit_message:
l3 router: implements l3 routervm plugin

This patch implements l3 routervm plugin(modular l3 router plugin).
TODO: unit tests are missing
This patch only implements common plugin part. Other parts will be followed
as patch series.

Change-Id: Ie3d2ac34691302974cc241d0771f266ce300b676
Partially-implements: blueprint l3-plugin-for-routervm

get_router_ids() should be called only in case agent doing a full sync. When is it called in your case?'}, {'account_id': 7016, 'date': '2016-04-18 22:34:12.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2:

In this case it is called during full_sync, when the agent restarts.
So if there was a snat_move when the agent was dead, and when the agent comes up, the agent tries to do a full sync and then during the full_sync it tries to call get-router-ids and that in turn is trying to reschedule the removed router from the agent to the same agent.'}, {'account_id': 5948, 'date': '2016-04-19 00:14:04.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2:

Well, that's the main purpose of the autoschedule feature: when some agent goes up it requests routers and server schedules all unhosted routers. It's the same for both dvr and legacy routers. So why dvr routers should differ? If autoscheduling is not desired it can be disabled through the config router_auto_schedule."}, {'account_id': 7016, 'date': '2016-04-19 15:19:05.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2:

I understand the config options and also its purpose. But the dvr routers should not be auto scheduled based on the original design.

So do you think to fix this bug (for stable/mitaka) we should ask everyone to first fix the config option and then use the patch to make it work.

What is the right way to go about. Then this would be also a document change.'}, {'account_id': 5948, 'date': '2016-04-19 18:13:33.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2:

Can you please describe the bug (assuming we have  https://review.openstack.org/#/c/285480/ applied) and steps to reproduce? I mean, I understood the initial problem: router is rescheduled right after it was manually removed from the agent, but with https://review.openstack.org/#/c/285480/ it should not happen.'}, {'account_id': 7016, 'date': '2016-04-19 23:30:41.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2:

Oleg:

The first case if we apply the assaf's patch 
https://review.openstack.org/#/c/285480/

Will prevent any router from immediately rescheduling to the host, when the agent is alive.

When the agent is dead and if we try to remove a router, then when the agent restarts, the full_sync_ call in the agent triggers 'get_router_ids" and this one intern calls the "auto_schedule_routers".

So any unscheduled routers are again scheduled to the agent. This happens, only when I have the router removed and have not added the router to another agent before the "agent" restarts.

How to reproduce this issue:
1. Single node devstack
2. Create a network/subnet and dvr router.
3. This should at least create snat_namespace, qrouter_namespace and dhcp_namespace on the node.
4. Apply my snat_move patch and assaf's patch to the neutron-server.
5. Now kill the agent(l3).
6. Now remove the router from the agent.
7. Then restart the agent, before and now you should see that the router is again scheduled to the host. This is triggered by the auto_schedule call in get_router_ids.'}, {'account_id': 5948, 'date': '2016-04-20 00:34:35.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2:

Ok, I see. So this will be the same for legacy routers, right? That is how autoscheduling works: when agent is started (or revived) it asks the server for routers and server will return all routers that are scheduled to the agent and also schedule all unscheduled routers. If this behavior is not desired then we have an option to switch it off via config. Why dvr routers should differ?'}, {'account_id': 7016, 'date': '2016-05-02 17:26:23.000000000', 'content': 'Abandoned

Abandon this patch, since another patch is taking care of it.'}]

commit_message:
Revert "Bring back dvr routers autoscheduling"

By introducing the auto-scheduling for DVR routers, the DVR routers are
constantly rescheduled to the agent, if we try to remove a router from
an agent and add to a different agent (manual move). Since the DVR
routers have router namespace and snat namespace, there should be a way
to remove just the snat_namespace and move it to a different node.

This was not possible with this patch. So we should probably revert this
patch.

This reverts commit 6fad8d3e36fb0eb26105bdfe699a33e48c721408.

Change-Id: I0c220505757dc8c59a1415ee1f54aa240b20ffeb

revisions:
[{'created': '2016-04-13 12:35:01.000000000', 'message': '[Verify] Using common glance and network wrappers everywhere

"Verify" related code uses common wrappers only in a few places.
So this commit makes this code use common wrappers everywhere.

Using glance wrapper to delete an image caused an issue with token
expiration. That is why the delete_image() method in the GlanceV1Wrapper
class was slightly changed. Namely, the image.delete() was replaced by
self.client.images.delete(image.id) like it is done in the corresponding
method in the GlanceV2Wrapper class. Also, now the _update_image() method
is used in utils.wait_for_status() like it is done in the delete_image()
method in the GlanceV2Wrapper class.

Change-Id: Ideb9b0ce68dc8bf76c4f718b85abc984604d058d

"Verify" related code uses common wrappers only in a few places.
So this commit makes this code use common wrappers everywhere.

Using glance wrapper to delete an image caused an issue with token
expiration. That is why the delete_image() method in the GlanceV1Wrapper
class was slightly changed. Namely, the image.delete() was replaced by
self.client.images.delete(image.id) like it is done in the corresponding
method in the GlanceV2Wrapper class. Also, now the _update_image() method
is used in utils.wait_for_status() like it is done in the delete_image()
method in the GlanceV2Wrapper class.

commit_message:
openstack-manuals: Adjust jobs

The master branch and the future mitaka branch do not have
any DocBook files, run checksyntax only on branches that have it
(Kilo/Liberty). Also, remove checklink job, it was only run on master
and is thus obsolete.

Change-Id: I9f5944eb9db06fe2ff9088f22048c198b2921237

commit_message:
Python 3: fix relative imports

On Python 3, imports are absolute by default. By default, OpenStack
coding style requires to use relative imports.

Fix imports two use the full "path" to relative imports.

Partially implements: blueprint trove-python3
Change-Id: I2866fdc1a39fb3a20d8384a4082ca468b57d92d3

[{'created': '2016-04-29 19:37:56.000000000', 'message': 'Make RPC call to abandon nested stack

Due to stacks being processable by multiple engines, resources in a
nested stack cannot be marked for retainment from the parent resource
of the nested stack. This patch makes the parent resource of the nested
stack call stack abandon instead of stack delete through the RPC client
so that nested stacks are deleted while nested stack resources are
retained.

Change-Id: I7103f46d86db35e08b014d9790215740fcae441d
Closes-bug: #1509912
'}]
commit_message:
Make RPC call to abandon nested stack

Due to stacks being processable by multiple engines, resources in a
nested stack cannot be marked for retainment from the parent resource
of the nested stack. This patch makes the parent resource of the nested
stack call stack abandon instead of stack delete through the RPC client
so that nested stacks are deleted while nested stack resources are
retained.

Change-Id: I7103f46d86db35e08b014d9790215740fcae441d
Closes-bug: #1509912

interfaces states.

commit_message:
Python3: Add support for unicode, basestring, long

Replaced basestring with six.string_types
Replaced (int, long) with six.integer_types
Replaced unicode with six.text_type

This patch is generated by the following tool using
'basestring', 'long' and 'unicode' options.

Manually replaced unicode(ex) with oslo_utils.encodeutils(ex)

https://github.com/haypo/sixer
Command:
python sixer.py -w 'basestring,long,unicode' trove/

Partially implements: blueprint trove-python3

Change-Id: I6fa42674060067663ef819247ea793ef3d8aa0da

First to be clear: my patch doesn't change the data used in unit tests on Python 2. b'str' is exactly the same than 'str' on Python 2.

amrith:
> I would like tests to be added that demonstrate that data encoded the 'old way' can be decrypted the 'new way'.

There is no "new way". Before, the code didn't work on Python 3, and the code has no effect on Python 2 if you only work on byte strings which is the native type for strings on Python 2.

Maybe this change adds a new feature on Python 2, you can now encode Unicode strings with non-ASCII characters. I didn't check what was the behaviour before, but I guess that Trove doesn't pass Unicode to crypto functions (but byte strings on Python 2).

> I submit to you therefore that you shouldn't modify these functions, but rather should create new ones for python34.

Duplicating the code for Python 2 and Python 3 is bad practice, it's very error prone. When a bug is fixed, it becomes possible that only one version is fixed (ex: only py2), not both.'}, {'account_id': 9107, 'date': '2016-03-29 12:30:44.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 2: Commit message was updated.'}, {'account_id': 9664, 'date': '2016-03-29 12:40:19.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2:

revisions:
[{'created': '2016-03-25 22:58:46.000000000', 'message': 'Port crypto_utils to Python 3

* pad_for_encryption(): replace chr() with six.int2byte() to get
  bytes on Python 3.
* use byte strings in tests
* Encode text encryption key to UTF-8
* Encode text data to UTF-8 to encrypt
* tox.ini: add test_common_extensions and test_crypto_utils
  to Python 3.4 (test_common_extensions already passed before).

Partially implements: blueprint trove-python3
Change-Id: I8e991994698d558177580595cf2c7da93ed1e1c8
'}, {'created': '2016-03-29 12:30:44.000000000', 'message': 'Port crypto_utils to Python 3

This change is backward compatible:

* Data encrypted with the old code can be decrypted with the new code
* Data encrypted with the new code can be decrypted with the old code

Effect on Python 2: add support for Unicode strings which contain
non-ASCII characters. Before functions failed with
UnicodeEncodeError.

Changes:

* pad_for_encryption(): replace chr() with six.int2byte() to get
  bytes on Python 3.
* use byte strings in tests
* Encode text encryption key to UTF-8
* Encode text data to UTF-8 to encrypt
* tox.ini: add test_common_extensions and test_crypto_utils
  to Python 3.4 (test_common_extensions already passed before).

Note: UTF-8 is the defacto standard encoding in OpenStack. It is

commit_message:
Port crypto_utils to Python 3

This change is backward compatible on Python 2:

* Data encrypted with the old code can be decrypted with the new code
* Data encrypted with the new code can be decrypted with the old code

Effect on Python 2: it now is possible to encode Unicode strings
which contain non-ASCII characters. Before encode_data() failed with
UnicodeEncodeError.

Changes:

* pad_for_encryption(): replace chr() with six.int2byte() to get
  bytes on Python 3.
* use byte strings in tests
* encode_data() now encodes data to UTF-8 (if it is Unicode)
* encrypt() and decrypt() now encode the encryption key to UTF-8 (if
  it's Unicode)
* encrypt() now encodes data to UTF-8 (if it's Unicode), it's only
  needed on Python 3 since encode_data() returns Unicode on Python 3.
* test_encode_decode_string(): test also Unicode
* Add new unit tests on encrypt() and decrypt() with known values and
  hardcoded IV.
* tox.ini: add test_common_extensions and test_crypto_utils
  to Python 3.4 (test_common_extensions already passed before).

Note: UTF-8 is the defacto standard encoding in OpenStack. It is
already used widely in all parts of OpenStack.

Partially implements: blueprint trove-python3
Change-Id: I8e991994698d558177580595cf2c7da93ed1e1c8

commit_message:
Fix up some typos in the proxy manifests

The introductory comments in the manifests for proxy keystone and
tempauth had some typos to be corrected. The proxy staticweb
comments accidentally called itself the manifest for cache_errors,
so fix that up as well.

Change-Id: I76c7c5201aa351ffcb060bf6ec5127aeda08ee2b

commit_message:
Use glance wrapper where appropriate

This makes several places (Nova, Cinder, verify) use the glance
wrapper while accessing glance, which fixes various Glance v2
bugs.

Change-Id: I83b46e223e85306b0e54f1d19cbbc7f21489e759
Co-Authored-By: Srinivas Sakhamuri <srini.openstack@gmail.com>
Co-Authored-By: Yaroslav Lobankov <ylobankov@mirantis.com>

commit_message:
Remove dependencies on kazoo and friends

Since kolla-mesos has been retired, there is no need in the code
base to keep the zookeeper implementation.  As a result, just remove
it.  If we were to keep it we need virtualenvs for that part of the
code base which installs the python dependencies related to it
for from-binary installs.

This just simplifies the implementation tremendously and culls dead
code.

Change-Id: Ieda226e652d67f5b5667112f4f2556f3171366d3
Closes-Bug: #1577194

revisions:
[{'created': '2016-04-26 14:25:33.000000000', 'message': 'Include MLDv2 in allowed ICMPv6 types

Multicast listener discovery (MLD) version 2 has superceded MLD v1 as it
support IGMPv3. MLDv2 uses a new ICMP type (143) for its report messages.
Adding this type to ICMPV6_ALLOWED_TYPES so it will be permitted by
default to egress through security groups.

Change-Id: I9caa234304fb621aa9ec0ab8156968b746a6b24a

commit_message:
Add constants for additional ICMPv6 types

Introducing additional constants for ICMPv6 types so integer literal
types can be removed in Neutron.

Change-Id: I9caa234304fb621aa9ec0ab8156968b746a6b24a

Backends may want to know the request method and based on that make some optimization. (Example: pre-fetch object content if file is too small enough during HEAD request anticipating a GET next OR detect a POST request that updates metadata of an existing object and do it in place) 

Further, allowing access to raw request will enable backends to interact with any custom middleware (without sysmeta persisting on disk).

An example: In swiftonfile use case, backends may want to set UID and GID of the object file on filesystem based on the authenticated keystone user (LDAP integration). This is just an example and isn't implemented today. Passing the request to backends will open up a lot of interesting possibilities in extending functionality. 

This is also a step towards preventing the interface being changed often as and when new features are added. I've seen DiskFile being changed when storage policies were implemented and again during EC."}, {'account_id': 2828, 'date': '2016-02-18 20:50:07.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 7.'}, {'account_id': 2828, 'date': '2016-02-19 00:43:06.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 8.'}, {'account_id': 2828, 'date': '2016-02-19 00:44:34.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 9.'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2016-02-19 03:07:10.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 9: Verified-1

commit_message:
go: ObjectEngine abstraction layer

This is a first pass at something analogous to swift's diskfile. The API is
probably not finalized.

There are a few interfaces you have to implement for a new ObjectEngine.
There's also a RegisterObjectEngine function to register a new object engine.
See go/objectserver/objengine.go for information.

I had to rejigger the AtomicFileWriter interface to make them friends, but this
way is fine too.

Change-Id: I032038b5e8a068aecdf8b29631f60ebf00cfb2ee

Fix auth_uri in client_keystone section

In contrast to other identity URIs, the auth_uri in the client_keystone
section of heat.conf must be the unversioned identity endpoint,
otherwise most resources will not work.

Change-Id: I9888e0b69c3ba2a60e3ac7bb84261ace6688b9e3

commit_message:
Corrected wrong parameter in docstring

In docstring of list() method of glanceclient/v1/images.py,
parameter 'return_request_id' used within **kwargs is
'return_req_id', not 'return_request_id'.

Changed 'return_request_id' to 'return_req_id'.

Change-Id: I7f4a2a5af1b13184c67fa81be971dc5139569f8b
Closes-Bug: 1573049

revisions:
[{'created': '2016-02-11 23:36:18.000000000', 'message': 'Create stackviz element and script in nodepool (WIP)

In order to get Stackviz running against tempest gate run data, it
will need to be pulled in its pre-built form (i.e. with npm deps
installed) from the nodepool images. This change adds a couple steps
to build Stackviz so that it is in a ready state for retrieval and use
on the logs server.

A future devstack-gate patch will pull the stackviz directory from the
nodepool images onto the logs server. This nodepool patch is required
first in order to prepare stackviz for download. Installing the npm
modules takes a considerable amount of time (~5-10 mins), so it is
best that this work is done on the images before gate jobs are run.

Change-Id: I9bc50b8eba696264d2b97ed20a37f28f4768abb8

commit_message:
Create stackviz element and script in nodepool

In order to get Stackviz running against tempest gate run data, it
will need to be pulled in its pre-built form (i.e. with npm deps
installed) from the nodepool images. This change adds a couple steps
to build Stackviz so that it is in a ready state for retrieval and use
on the logs server.

A future devstack-gate patch will pull the stackviz directory from the
nodepool images onto the logs server. This nodepool patch is required
first in order to prepare stackviz for download. Installing the npm
modules takes a considerable amount of time (~5-10 mins), so it is
best that this work is done on the images before gate jobs are run.

Change-Id: I9bc50b8eba696264d2b97ed20a37f28f4768abb8

commit_message:
Fix revert migration if flavor deleted

After an instance is created, the flavor could be deleted.  But
operations still need to be able to occur against the VM when that
occurs.  A new test in Tempest showed that we had been using the
incorrect (and potentially deleted) flavor when a resize/migration was
reverting.

This change updates the code to use the flavor that is stored on the
instance itself.

Change-Id: I16254d8eb74a724e3e0a538f47259e9627c4233a
Closes-Bug: 1570748
(cherry picked from commit e72a505860b2f7ce2dd4a492f65d426f8b091e1f)
Conflicts:
	nova_powervm/tests/virt/powervm/test_driver.py

commit_message:
Only install docker in case it is not installed

Add a conditional statement in devstack plugin to avoid install docker
in the host if it is already installed.

Change-Id: I27b2f576a3efa3f404bb0b55722b587c7b250997
Signed-off-by: Jaume Devesa <devvesa@gmail.com>

commit_message:
NetApp: DR look up config via host name

In multibackend config, the cDOT driver looks for stanzas with the
share_backend_name as the stanza name (assuming that that's the
hostname, which it isn't).

There needs to be a separation between these since
share_backend_name and stanza names can be different.

Change-Id: Id1c4380c5ac01a0b64645d249a7b61b4c2a62226
Closes-Bug: 1568997

commit_message:
Heat params are different in swarm master and swarm node

Heat parameters are different in swarm master and swarm node.
So we should use different scripts to write the heat parameters.

Change-Id: I81625613913773e627d96f54374ae57af6fe64d3
Closes-Bug: #1571582

commit_message:
Adding support for OVS Hybrid binding

Allows the OVS binding script to recognize if it
has to do hybrid binding or not and operate accordingly.

Closes-Bug: #1535828
Change-Id: I7c7d7b115b546c136a07880bc568662558dbc950

commit_message:
Enhances get_meters to return unique meters

Enhances get_meters in the storage layer
and API to accept a unique flag and return
back a list of unique meters for clients like
Horizon to consume.

DocImpact
Change-Id: Ifdcb907df867ae650eae733bc7b635a283939064
Closes-Bug: 1506959
(cherry picked from commit 52f48485eeed50dfa4705fc73e278214eb9a7f00)

commit_message:
move EventFilter to event storage namespace

There is no reason to put EventFilter under metering storage
namespace, it is not common for the two storages. Let's move it
to the place it should be.

Change-Id: Ibf16e9b4bbf33fd2afe036dcfbd85d1d28e17c9d

commit_message:
Handle multi Ethernets case in the gate

rax-iad node has two Ethernets, but others not. Detect the private
Ethernet by using script.

Closes-Bug: #1561563
Change-Id: I7c5d241f2b1a21f97512e52c487d875dd270011b

commit_message:
Verify config support keystone on subpath

verify-config should support keystone running on a subpath.
Currently it doesn't because it strips the entire path from the
identity endpoint in the catalog when calculating the unversioned
endpoint. The fix is to only strip off the last part of the path.

Change-Id: I0d24f83ea3243b8eeee50f8bfec28326be7c7292

commit_message:
add a bandit environment to tox

This change is being proposed as part of the OpenStack Security Project
working session at the Austin 2016 summit. It adds support for running
the bandit[1] security linting tool against the python-openstackclient
codebase. This change adds a targetted environment for bandit and also
adds bandit as part of the pep8 job.

The bandit configuration has been tailored to exclude tests that are
currently producing warning against the codebase. These issues will be
followed up with bug reports and patches.

[1]: https://wiki.openstack.org/wiki/Security/Projects/Bandit

Depends-On: Iccd81c17e84df03d249c1012277dad9cb68c5845
Change-Id: I691829c1224557d1d239c9f665ac539d0f13c4d3

commit_message:
workaround to deploy libffi-devel and  openssl-devel

Until https://review.openstack.org/#/c/311734/ is merged, we need to
deploy libffi-devel and openssl-devel manually otherwise ansible can't
be installed from pip, and CI is broken.

Change-Id: I992c4354038414f20f0377b57290470f9dc9942d

[{'created': '2016-05-02 11:52:13.000000000', 'message': "Allow compute driver to load correctly

In certain environments the load order can be confused between nova and
nova_powervm (now that nova_powervm has a nova/ source path).

This can cause boot issues where 'No module named cmd.compute' can be
thrown because the python code is looking in nova-powervm/nova for that
driver.

This change extends the declare_namespace code to allow for the other
projects to properly load.

This was affecting the PowerVM CI system and not allowing the systems to
properly load.

Change-Id: I4695814ad9ded96a6bb731b2a47f7050fedd8d85
"}]
commit_message:
Allow compute driver to load correctly

In certain environments the load order can be confused between nova and
nova_powervm (now that nova_powervm has a nova/ source path).

This can cause boot issues where 'No module named cmd.compute' can be
thrown because the python code is looking in nova-powervm/nova for that
driver.

This change extends the declare_namespace code to allow for the other
projects to properly load.

This was affecting the PowerVM CI system and not allowing the systems to
properly load.

Change-Id: I4695814ad9ded96a6bb731b2a47f7050fedd8d85

commit_message:
RGW >= Jewel requires pool names prefixed with zone

When deploying Jewel RGW (10.*) or above, pool names are
expected to be prefixed by the RGW client zone name.

Closes-Bug: 1573549
Change-Id: I01fa558b2f259deb243267ba7d714f7b4df5df75

commit_message:
Revert "Clean port dns_name in case of port detach"

This patch breaks any neutron plugin that does not support the extension
dns-integration. With this patch in place when update_port is called with
'dns_name' neutron-server will raise a BadRequest as dns_name is only part of
the api if a plugin is using this extension. Instead we should be checking
if a plugin has this extension loaded and if so  append dns_name: ''

Related-Bug: #1575195

This reverts commit fc66e7eb411eb8e99767c062ab8d0263738d5558.

Change-Id: I817b40892cd414eee281c1f0dad4f4bb6f1d21b2

Segments uploaded by swiftclient are expected to have a many-to-one

commit_message:
Identify segments uploaded via swiftclient

...using a new "application/swiftclient-segment" content-type.

Segments uploaded by swiftclient are expected to have a many-to-one
relationship to large objects, rather than the more-general many-to-many
relationship that SLO and DLO generally allow. Later, we may use this
information to make more intelligent decisions, such as when to
automatically clean up segments.

Change-Id: Ie56a3aa10065db754ac572cc37d93f2c901aac60

(3 comments)'}, {'account_id': 4393, 'date': '2016-02-18 17:24:55.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 24:

As far as I know, the removed objects end up going over the wire as part of an instance, right? That means we definitely cannot remove them until Newton, assuming we fix Mitaka to never (ever) send those objects over the wire. If Mitaka never sends them, it has to at least tolerate an older Liberty client sending them. Once we're out of that window then we could remove them.

I think this patch should be about removing any static code that works with the IDs, fixing any code that would end up with one of these objects sent over the wire to not send, and  then marking things as to-be-removed in newton."}, {'account_id': 4393, 'date': '2016-02-18 17:25:53.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 29: Code-Review-1

commit_message:
remove EC2 legacy code

continue of removing legacy ec2 code from nova.
Object 'EC2Ids' has been cleaned up and left as dumb object
with its properties not to break compatibility.
These objects was only used by the ec2-api and s3 services.

UpgradeImpact
Change-Id: If74f840b26f929a981ea8d5c55d5c15a07784237

commit_message:
Pin openstack-doc-tools

Future releases of openstack-doc-tools will not
support DocBook publishing, pin the version.

Change-Id: Ia6bcf92c5c8dbc96794864d4261989fbdcaf1fd6

Remove glossary handling

The DocBook XML glossary is gone, remove the special support in our
tools for it.

commit_message:
Remove feeds not reachable and add script to test feed URLs

The following feed URLs are not longer available:

* http://blog.hendrikvolkmer.de/feed/OpenStack/atom.xml - HTTP Error 404: Not Found
* http://blog.leafe.com/category/openstack/feed/ - HTTP Error 404: Not Found
* http://www.jasondotstar.com/feed.openstack.xml - HTTP Error 404: Not Found
* http://cpallar.es/tagged/openstack/rss - HTTP Error 404: Not Found
* http://www.solinea.com/blog/topic/open-source-openstack/rss.xml - HTTP Error 404: Not Found
* http://ayenson.blogspot.com/feeds/posts/default/-/Openstack - HTTP Error 404: Not Found
* https://swiftstack.com/blog/categories/planetopenstack/atom.xml - HTTP Error 404: Not Found
* http://inaugust.com/feed/rss2_0?tag=openstack - HTTP Error 404: Not Found

Fixed some syntax errors as well.

Change-Id: Ied2da3c8033d094cb02cb9cc1dfe9ff6eed7ef5a

commit_message:
Add VirtualBMC project under Ironic

VirtualBMC is a utility that allows virtual/fake BMCs to be
created handling the IPMI commands and converting it to calls to the
python-libvirt library. The project was created to allow drivers using
the IPMI protocol to be tested in the Ironic gate.

Change-Id: I24349ce1b5c0332157f1bf8bd0613338a15495e4
Depends-On: Idf02cb28316be1846bb5fa1988c3d47ce6f9c54c

[{'created': '2016-04-02 16:03:10.000000000', 'message': "Change kolla to release:cycle-with-milestones

The openstack/kolla repository has followed the
release:cycle_with_milestones schedule +/- 1-3 days for all
milestones in Liberty and Mitaka except where the PTL was ill
with a root canal that failed causing Mitaka-1 to be tagged
far later then it should have been. In that case, the PTL
added backup release managers (asalkeld inc0 and rhallisey)
so that wouldn't occur in the future.

For the moment we will work around the requirement for a release
extension that as requested by deployment projects in a different
review by releasing a potentially DOA (for binary builds only) release
that potentially includes references to rc releases of OpenStack
projects that have not yet released their stable release.

We will release on upstream schedules, and if necessary release
a z stream fixing these problems shortly after the deadlines.

Change-Id: Ibc6837b46c70c3458f8efdb2e79e7bd3a3b3c189

commit_message:
Change kolla to release:cycle-trailing

The openstack/kolla repository has followed the
release:cycle_with_milestones schedule +/- 1-3 days for all
milestones in Liberty and Mitaka except where the PTL was ill
with a root canal that failed causing Mitaka-1 to be tagged
far later then it should have been. In that case, the PTL
added backup release managers (asalkeld inc0 and rhallisey)
so that wouldn't occur in the future.

Now that Doug has proposed cycle-trailing, we can meet that

Depends-On: I783f6f6d55ab33386851910d09bf0e3f0efda404
Change-Id: Ibc6837b46c70c3458f8efdb2e79e7bd3a3b3c189

revisions:
[{'created': '2016-03-24 21:57:34.000000000', 'message': "Update release tags for some Puppet OpenStack modules

Each Puppet OpenStack module usually has this lifecycle:

- creation of the module: basic structure
- adding features specific to the component to deploy
- adding functional testing, in integration CI if possible so Tempest is
  run, otherwise in beaker jobs only, so we test basic deployments.

Once the module reachs some maturity (used by our Community, regular
contributions, advanced testing), we start producing releases.

Until now, we have 24 modules that we consider mature enough to release
them.

Our release cycle is following OpenStack releases, every 6 months.
At each release, we create a stable branch and our team manage the
backports.
We have a backport policy [1] and a Wiki page [2] documenting the
modules releases.

We would like to apply for 2 release tags:

1) release:cycle-with-intermediary [3]
Our group commits to produce a release to match the end of the 6-month
development cycle. Mitaka is a good example where we're about to release
in the same time as other projects.

2) release:has-stable-branches [4]
- We cut a stable branch from their last release in a given
development cycle, which is 6 months.
- Our team commits to help maintain the stable branches by proposing
backports for critical issues and reviewing those (we have a lot of
operators and people doing production deployments that need backports,
we're taking care of them).

You'll notice in this patch some modules are not applying, because we
don't consider them mature enough or they don't need releases (some
repositories are not deliverables).

[1] https://wiki.openstack.org/wiki/Puppet/Backport_policy
(2] https://wiki.openstack.org/wiki/Puppet/releases)
[3] http://governance.openstack.org/reference/tags/release_cycle-with-intermediary.html#requirements
[4] http://governance.openstack.org/reference/tags/release_has-stable-branches.html#requirements

Change-Id: Ic6b539f7db58077f102ba9536c862363a5831d5a

commit_message:
Update release tags for some Puppet OpenStack modules

Each Puppet OpenStack module usually has this lifecycle:

- creation of the module: basic structure
- adding features specific to the component to deploy
- adding functional testing, in integration CI if possible so Tempest is
  run, otherwise in beaker jobs only, so we test basic deployments.

Once the module reachs some maturity (used by our Community, regular
contributions, advanced testing), we start producing releases.

Until now, we have 24 modules that we consider mature enough to release
them.

Our release cycle is following OpenStack releases, every 6 months.
At each release, we create a stable branch and our team manage the
backports.
We have a backport policy [1] and a Wiki page [2] documenting the
modules releases.

We would like to apply for 1 release tag:
release:cycle-trailing

Our group already commits to produce a release to match the end of the 6-month
development cycle. Mitaka is a good example where we're about to release
in the same time as other projects.
Though having a small time window after official release will help us to
produce better releases, because of all dependencies that we have
(mostly upstream packaging).

You'll notice in this patch some modules are not applying, because we
don't consider them mature enough or they don't need releases (some
repositories are not deliverables).

[1] https://wiki.openstack.org/wiki/Puppet/Backport_policy
[2] https://wiki.openstack.org/wiki/Puppet/releases

Change-Id: Ic6b539f7db58077f102ba9536c862363a5831d5a

commit_message:
Add support for booting bare metals from Cinder volume

This commit proposes changes to Nova Ironic virt driver
to support booting from Cinder volume (in tandem with
other changes proposed in Ironic).

Co-Authored-By: Satoru Moriya <satoru.moriya.br@hitachi.com>
Change-Id: I11d37595d11b536bbe0f986a3a814bed2b3a2650
Implements: blueprint ironic-boot-from-volume
Depends-On: Ibf50be735905f868e0d523ab16353a6b5cc300af

commit_message:
Only set port dns_name if dns extension enabled

Setting dns_name on a port when the neutron plugin doesn't
support the DNS Integration extension causes an error.  This is
breaking the networking-ovn neutron plugin gate job.  Updated
the code to only set the port dns_name if the extension exists.

Change-Id: I45d96ee7c4dfb81014599eeaf4cefcbf864c1332
Closes-Bug: #1575195

commit_message:
Fix possible masters search

OCF RA shall not evaluate "0" UUIDs.
Fix getting UUID by including "wsrep_start_position" as well.

Closes-bug: #1576244

Change-Id: Ide4b43f71f74431fa8017ea05c9ea52c05b96a32
Signed-off-by: Bogdan Dobrelya <bdobrelia@mirantis.com>

commit_message:
Retire kolla-mesos project

The kolla-mesos project has been retired via majoirty vote of the
core reviewer team here:
http://lists.openstack.org/pipermail/openstack-dev/2016-April/093180.html

Following the process for retiring a project here:
http://docs.openstack.org/infra/manual/drivers.html#retiring-a-project

Change-Id: Ief32a399d0ff57332864c65d5380269051e24b6b

[{'created': '2016-01-15 01:55:57.000000000', 'message': "Ensure floating IPs only use IPv4 addresses

Description:
Presently Neutron doesn't validate the address family of floating IP
addresses or the internal addresses they are associated with. It merely
associates the first IP of the floating IP's port with the first IP of
the internal port, unless a specified fixed IP is specified. This can
lead to incorrect or poorly defined behavior when IPv6 is present.

The existing L3 agent implementation only manages IPv4 NAT rules. While
IPv6 NAT and NAT protocol translation are possible, the existing
implementation does not support these configurations.

Presently a floating IP can be created on an IPv6 only external network
or associated with an IPv6 fixed IP, but the L3 agent is unable to bind
these configurations.

Implementation:
When creating and updating a floating IP, only consider IPv4 addresses
on both the floating IPs port and the internal port he floating IP is
associated with. Additionally disallow creating floating IPs on networks
without any IPv4 subnets, since these floating IPs could not be
allocated an IPv4 address.

DocImpact
APIImpact

commit_message:
Ensure floating IPs only use IPv4 addresses

Description:
Presently Neutron doesn't validate the address family of floating IP
addresses or the internal addresses they are associated with. It merely
associates the first IP of the floating IP's port with the first IP of
the internal port, unless a specified fixed IP is specified. This can
lead to incorrect or poorly defined behavior when IPv6 is present.

The existing L3 agent implementation only manages IPv4 NAT rules. While
IPv6 NAT and NAT protocol translation are possible, the existing
implementation does not support these configurations.

Presently a floating IP can be created on an IPv6 only external network
or associated with an IPv6 fixed IP, but the L3 agent is unable to bind
these configurations.

Implementation:
When creating and updating a floating IP, only consider IPv4 addresses
on both the floating IPs port and the internal port he floating IP is
associated with. Additionally disallow creating floating IPs on networks
without any IPv4 subnets, since these floating IPs could not be
allocated an IPv4 address.

DocImpact
APIImpact

Co-Authored-By: Bradley Jones <jones.bradley@me.com>
Change-Id: I79b28a304b38ecdafc17eddc41213df1c24ec202
Related-Bug: #1437855
Closes-Bug: #1323766
Closes-Bug: #1469322
(cherry picked from commit 4cdc71e7d0e5220a5f12ee2dfea1ff3db045c041)

commit_message:
Enable check for E226

By default, pep8.py ignores E226.
Enabled E226 by adding an ignore clause to tox.ini so that
pep8 by default ignore list gets overridden by what we specify.

TrivialFix
Change-Id: I3efedbec845de7810acd345b98cb302c2247f5bd

commit_message:
Check for worker_service initialization

When stopping the engine check if the worker_service is
intialized or not before stopping it.

Change-Id: I876c2cef4bf6589b9bc45f58b5cd52ed0323c9e9
Closes-Bug: #1572851

commit_message:
WIP: Implement get_vifs_by_instance for neutron API

Listing virtual interfaces via the os-virtual-interfaces API
does not work when using neutron as the network API.

For the sake of feature parity and cloud interop, we should
implement this simple API.

WIP since this probably requires a microversion...

Change-Id: Ia017b2f390814c965e06afbc28235e61a04dd60a
Closes-Bug: #1183436

commit_message:
Implement os-virtual-interfaces for Neutron

Requesting a GET to the os-virtual-interfaces API in Nova fails with a 400 if
Neutron is configured as the network API. We should implement the network API
for Neutron so we have feature parity and interoperability between different
clouds where one is running nova-network and another is running Neutron.

Spec for blueprint implement-os-virtual-interfaces-for-neutron

Change-Id: Ice9a9588f14479ef2b5fc5fc0c9c91ba72d07390

commit_message:
Provide an updated mission for magnum

This mission and service incorporated in this change
seem to better define what magnum is at its current state
and what the session at seemed to agree upon:

https://etherpad.openstack.org/p/newton-magnum-unified-abstraction

The wording can be adjusted but I think it more clearly
and explicitly defines what magnum is (and will help in avoiding
the confusion for others in the future).

Change-Id: Ice43210a134d0ef93cdc75e3383c6fba839ed2fc

commit_message:
[Trivial] replace logging with oslo.log

oslo.log provides more features and is a fundamental recommended
library to use.

Also the library oslo.log provides compatibility for log levels,
logging namespace is not needed.

Change-Id: I37439260d33024aee46c81f9b1db3130403d220c

We only set the dns_name on the port if the "DNS Integration"
extension is enabled, so we should only reset it on the port
when unbinding if the extension is enabled, otherwise some

commit_message:
Only reset dns_name when unbinding port if DNS is integrated

We only set the dns_name on the port if the "DNS Integration"
extension is enabled, so we should only reset it on the port
when unbinding if the extension is enabled, otherwise some
Neutron stadium plugins will fail since they don't expect
the 'dns_name' attribute to be on the port.

Change-Id: I7451fbfad53236e9e147a0387dac45ae97f3e75b
Closes-Bug: #1574565

commit_message:
Adding "security_group_default_rules" parameter

This patch added "security_group_default_rules" parameter into
"List default security group rules", "Create default security group rule"
and "Show default security group rule details". This value was missed.

Closes-Bug: #1564742

Change-Id: I2ac2d68e85e61a71989bc61f00bc121a0f3bd131

This commit fixes the conf file open mode when "tempest init" command
runs. The original open mode "w" truncates its file. We should use 'a'
for updating a file instead.

Change-Id: I033454950cf58615e212d8c9fdf96765cf45c454
'}]
commit_message:
Fix conf file open mode when "tempest init"

This commit fixes the conf file open mode when "tempest init" command
runs. The original open mode "w" truncates its file. We should use 'a'
for updating a file instead.

Change-Id: I033454950cf58615e212d8c9fdf96765cf45c454

Optimize security group fw rules

Instead of multiple rules build for TCP ALL or UDP ALL rule only
one rule will be build for each case.

    Your patch will now be tested automatically by OpenStack testing frameworks

    developers. They will give you feedback and may require you to refine it.

    People seldom get their patch approved on the first try, so don't be
    concerned if requested to make corrections. Feel free to modify your patch
    and resubmit a new change-set.

    Patches usually take 3 to 7 days to be reviewed so be patient and be
    available on IRC to ask and answer questions about your work. Also it
    takes generally at least a couple of weeks for cores to get around to
    reviewing code. The more you participate in the community the more
    rewarding it is for you. You may also notice that the more you get to know
    people and get to be known, the faster your patches will be reviewed and
    eventually approved. Get to know others and become known by doing code
    reviews: anybody can do it, and it's a great way to learn the code base.

    Thanks again for supporting OpenStack, we look forward to working with you.

commit_message:
Only update port of DHCP agent on removed network

remove_network_from_dhcp_agent should only update the port
for the agent on the network it is being removed from.
Otherwise the code will affect ports that have nothing to
do with the network that is being unbound.

Closes-Bug: #1570347
Change-Id: I6b7df4e640711e8ff4f9dd6edbfa53ad82e44fd2

Cinder notification to Ceilometer has been supported for a long time,
this patch adds some scenario test for it.

commit_message:
Fix NoSuchOptError when referring to conf.neutron.auth_plugin

We already replaced 'auth_plugin' with 'auth_type'[1], now an
oslo_config.cfg.NoSuchOptError will be threw up when referring to
conf.neutron.auth_plugin.

This commit replace the usage of conf.neutron.auth_plugin by
conf.neutron.auth_type.

[1]https://github.com/openstack/keystoneauth/commit/a56ed4218aef5a2e528aa682cea967e767dca923

Change-Id: I0b72f278ba8e28508274079ff284042fb9ea3d64
Closes-Bug: #1574988

Hi.  How are the rst files generated?
Thanks.'}, {'account_id': 15293, 'date': '2016-04-28 12:37:44.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3:

Do you really need the individual yaml files?  Seems like all the files got dumped from the script create_parameters.'}, {'account_id': 964, 'date': '2016-04-28 14:04:21.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3:

The RST comes from the template in create_yaml_parameters.py I believe.

The idea for this patch is that people can download the api-ref/source/<service> directory and use that as their starting point, taking the files out of here to their own repo. It means we need to freeze the api-site/api-ref directory and not accept patches, which I'll send to the mailing list once we sense this is "good enough" -- and I think it can be. I've talked to people who can test, hopefully in the next few weeks, to be sure.'}, {'account_id': 964, 'date': '2016-04-28 14:05:32.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 3:

I could also move this over to api-site as a place for people to download, since it's complete fakery to have these in fairy-slipper. :) I hand-copied and hand-deleted files to get these files together. So maybe it's better to put into api-site?"}, {'account_id': 15293, 'date': '2016-04-28 14:13:29.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 3:

Yes, the rst was generated from create_yaml_parameters. The rst generation is a bit incomplete here.
I don't think it makes sense to leave the generated files in this repo, unless they are temporarily housed here until the files are copied to the respective repos.  Why not copy over the files now to the repos as part of the migration, unless there are questions about where to put the files for publishing."}, {'account_id': 964, 'date': '2016-04-28 14:17:55.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 3:

I have considered patching all the repos, but need to move carefully to make sure we find owners for all the API reference, and so I'm not going to make the 12 patches myself since it would take about 3 months to get them landed. The idea is to find owners, and at the Summit there has been a lot of interest, so I think it'll be okay. I do think this content should go to api-site since it's content. I'll work on that today."}, {'account_id': 964, 'date': '2016-04-28 15:36:33.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 3:

Oh, nice idea! I'll place those as well."}, {'account_id': 15293, 'date': '2016-04-29 13:32:35.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3: -Code-Review

If it is easier, leave the files here.
What about adding the publishing tool in a separate patch, so that
the files can be tested.'}, {'account_id': 15293, 'date': '2016-04-29 15:48:57.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3:

I think it would be straightforward to update the create_yaml_parameters script to generate the .inc file from the associated .rst files.  There would be fewer rst files to edit and the composite file would be ready to use by the publishing tools.  Will try this out in another patch.'}, {'account_id': 964, 'date': '2016-04-29 16:05:20.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 3:

Sure, give it a try. I'm trying out the image files now, and have a patch nearly ready for api-site. Working session is at 2 this afternoon Central time, and should have more tests done by then."}, {'account_id': 15293, 'date': '2016-04-29 17:50:51.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3:

I have inc files publishing, see patch:
https://review.openstack.org/311214'}, {'account_id': 964, 'date': '2016-04-30 16:41:36.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3: Workflow-1'}, {'account_id': 964, 'date': '2016-05-01 04:43:02.000000000', 'content': 'Abandoned

Replacing with https://review.openstack.org/311596 in api-site instead of fairy-slipper.'}]
